Coronavirus (COVID-19) and Pandemic Flu FAQ

We will update this page regularly as new information and new questions emerge. 
Updated: April 15, 2020 (9:19 pm)

All schools CLOSED in person for the rest of the school year. Distance Learning will begin April 13 and go through the end of the school year.

Q. I have questions...how can I get answers?
First, check the FAQ pages:
English: http://bit.ly/32Tr0am 
Espaol: http://bit.ly/3cC0K8T
If you cant find the answer, email Gregg Koskela. Please be patient as we work to find answers.
koskelag@newberg.k12.or.us

We encourage you to remain home as much as possible, maintain social distance, wash hands frequently, and avoid touching your face. The purpose of the governors order is for everyone, even people healthy and without symptoms, to stay away from others and slow the spread of the Coronavirus. 

See the attached graphic about social distancing. For more details, read this.

Q. Will CPRD Care be open?
CPRD is opening childcare for essential needs on Monday March 30. Everyone will need to re-enroll for the limited spaces available.
Called Camp Care Essentials, this day care program will run MondayFriday, 7:30 am to 6:00 pm. Pre-K children ages 3-6 will be at Chehalem Community Center; grade school children ages 512 will be at Sander Estate House in Dundee or Chehalem Youth Building in Newberg.
Cost:
$47 per day (registered in advance)
$99 1-week part-time rate (includes up to 19 hours per week of child care)
$125 1-week full-time rate (20 or more hours a week) 
 Registration is open now and closes when the maximum enrollment of ten children per pod/club is met. Registration is online only at the link: https://bit.ly/39jhhvK 
For questions or assistance with online enrollment, contact Chehalem Aquatic and Fitness Center at 503 537-2909 between the hours of 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. Monday through Friday, or email registration@cprdnewberg.org.


Q. Are we providing food to students during the closure? How will it be delivered/accessed?
Anyone ages 1-18 can receive a free meal for breakfast and lunch, Monday through Friday. 

We are excited to let you know about two expansions to our food service that began Wednesday, April 1. We added 11 new food distribution sites to the 5 sites that have been open. In addition, all sites will distribute two free meals (breakfast and lunch) in grab-and-go containers to anyone age 18 and under.

These new sites have been chosen to reach areas where the need is greatest. We will also begin contacts next week with all our students. These contacts will let us know which students still are not being reached so that we can make plans to meet the food needs of our students.

Look for the yellow school bus at sites that arent at a school building to pick up your food. Please do not congregate closely. Leave at least 6 feet of social distance at all times when you pick up your food.

Q. Are there any other resources for food?
As of March 13, several churches are still planning to provide free meals. Here is the schedule:
Monday Dinner: (every) Zion Lutheran Church (301 S. River) 5:30pm-6:30pm 
Tuesday Dinner: (2nd & 4th Tuesday of each month) Dundee Community Center (1026 Hwy 99W Dundee) 5:30pm-6:30pm (1st, 3rd and 5th Tuesdays) Joyful Servant Lutheran Church (1716 Villa Rd.) 5:30pm-6:30pm.
Wednesday Dinner: (every) - River Street Church of God (715 S. River) 6:00pm-7:00pm
Thursday Dinner: (every)- Newberg Christian Church (2315 Villa Rd) 4:30-pm-5:45pm
Friday Dinner: (every)- St. Peter Catholic Church (2315 N Main St) 5:30pm-6:30pm

Also, many may now qualify for free/reduced meals through the Federal Government. We want students to have their food needs met. We encourage you to fill out the form now, and it will continue to qualify you through next school year: https://bit.ly/3abwvDz 

Q. What are the goals of Distance Learning for All?
Here is our biggest encouragement to all the students and families making your way through this new normal: take a deep breath, do as much as you can, and know that our goal for Distance Learning for All is only to help, and not harm in any way. Our teachers are working together to concentrate on the most essential standards, the most important things youll need to learn as you move on to the next grade. We cant do it all, but we can cover essentials. When were all back together in person, we will work hard together to make up ground and move forward. 

We know parents, guardians, and caregivers arent trained as teachers and have other responsibilities, and we are creating materials to be as easy to use as possible. However, if things are confusing for parents or students, we dont want to add to the anxiety of this time. Do the best you can, as all of us are!

Q. What kinds of things will students be doing?
It will vary depending on the grade level. Generally, all students will have about two lessons per week in each subject/class. Lessons are designed to be completed at your own pace and on your own schedule through the week. Each lesson is designed to take roughly 30 minutes, varying by grade level and subject. 

Each teacher at the secondary level (middle and high school) will also schedule video conference sessions in Google Meets where students will participate at the same time as other students. These face-to-face times over the internet will be used for help sessions and for connecting with students to see how they are doing. Attendance in these sessions is not required, but they are intended as a way to provide support to students and families in their distance learning work. 

Teachers are working together across the district to create consistent lessons by grade and subject. This means, for example, that you might have a video in your classroom from a different teacher than you are used to. You can be sure that your teacher was part of the group that planned the material you are learning from.

Your individual school and your teachers will be giving more specific information. We know there will be lots to learn and lots of questions. We are here to learn from each other and to help. You can contact your teacher or your school for assistance. Know that we wish we could be together face-to-face, but we are doing this for everyones health and safety in this time of a pandemic.

Q. How will students access their work?
Most students will use Google Classroom to access all their assignments and resources. Google Classroom is a Learning Management System that organizes lessons, videos, links, and other resources into individual assignments and units. Kindergarten through 2nd grade students will get their assignments and resources from their teacher in SeeSaw. Some of our elementary classrooms were already using SeeSaw as a way to share what was happening at school with people at home. This will expand that use. Some will be familiar with it, while for others it will be brand new.

Students, your school email address will be essential to use during this time of Distance Learning. Communication from your teachers will be to that address, and you will use that account to login to resources. We know some students, especially elementary students, may never have used that account. Parents/Guardians can call your school to get the login information for your student. 

Q. I dont know what my child is supposed to be doing. Its hard to keep track of all the emails from teachers. Is there one spot that can give me an overview?
Yes! Our teachers have created overview templates for the week, to share the goals and objectives and the activities to do. Its all organized by grade and subject.

Youll still need to login to Google Classroom or SeeSaw to get the activities, but these overviews are in English and Spanish to help parents, guardians, and caregivers have an easy way to find what is happening for the week: https://bit.ly/2XD6wST 

Parents can also support by helping students maintain a basic daily schedule for learning. All of us are out of routine, and that in itself creates anxiety. We encourage parents to make a simple schedule for learning and other fun.

Q. What is the suggested daily schedule for students?
Everyone will be a little different, depending on work schedules at home, grade level, individual class schedules, etc. But here are some rough ideas for what it could look like:

For Elementary students

Each day will have a different focus:
Mondays and Wednesdays - Humanities (Literacy and Social Studies), PE/Health
Tuesdays and Thursdays - Math, Science, Music
Friday: Social Emotional Learning (SEL) Activities / Teacher Office Hours

For Middle and High School Students:

Middle and High School students will focus on different periods on different days. Monday: Periods 1 and 2. Tuesday: Periods 3 and 4. Wednesday: Periods 5 and 6. Thursday: Period 7. Friday: Social Emotional Learning (SEL). (Catalyst students have a different schedule and should refer to communication from your school.)

Q. I need help with Google Classroom and/or SeeSaw.
We will include help for accessing both Google Classroom and SeeSaw in the resources section on the District website. Go to http://bit.do/newberg and look for the Student/Family Tech Support page on the Learning Resource Site. Or click here: https://bit.ly/2xjUkvt

Q. My student is on an IEP. How will you support my student?
In several ways. Special Education teachers are part of the teams creating lessons, and are working to include elements in the lessons that support all students. Special Education teachers are also working hard on an individual basis for each student to meet needs. Staff will be in contact with you for support. Case managers will be scheduling meetings and rescheduling missed meetings. Also, please take a look at our district page at http://bit.do/newberg for Special Education Resources and Activities for students.

Q. My student needs English Language Development support. How will you support my student?
In several ways. EL teachers are part of the teams creating lessons, and are working to include elements in lessons that support all students. EL teachers will also be connecting with students to provide support and meet student needs.

Q. Is this Distance Learning for All required?
We expect our students to participate, and are continuing to work on removing barriers so that all students are able to participate.

Q. Will the Distance Learning for All work be graded?
Grading is proving very complicated to make sure it is done in an equitable way. We want to evaluate based on learning of standards, not on access to the learning or access to the technology. We want students engaged in learning, while keeping anxiety about performance as low as possible.

The Oregon Department of Education (ODE) has not yet released complete guidance for grading. They have indicated that for grades 6-12, students will receive a grade of pass or incomplete, based on the entire semester. Teachers will be evaluating and selecting the key standards that need to be demonstrated as proficient in order to receive a passing grade. Evidence for those standards can be from either the in-person class time before March 13, or during Distance Learning for All. This semester will not affect a students cumulative GPA.

If a student receives an incomplete grade because certain key standards were not demonstrated, they will have the opportunity to demonstrate proficiency either this spring or summer, or again when we return in the fall. When proficiency is demonstrated, the grade for this semester will be changed to pass. A grade of incomplete will not affect promotion to the next grade level during this unique situation. In middle school or high school, it may affect which course a student is placed in when we return to in-person learning.

For most students, not including the semester in the cumulative GPA is helpful. For some students who were hoping to raise their GPA to qualify for the Oregon Promise credit for college, there may be anxiety. The Office of Student Access and Completion (OSAC) has said they will provide a way for our high school registrar to indicate that it was mathematically possible for a student to have raised their cumulative, unweighted GPA to 2.50 if grades had been given this semester instead of pass/incomplete. This will qualify a student for Oregon Promise. Our high school staff will be contacting every senior no later than April 30 with details about graduation requirements and these types of GPA issues.

ODE has not yet given indication for how we are to handle Elementary progress marks. Please know our goal is for students to be engaged in learning, while keeping anxiety about performance as low as possible.

Q. What about seniors? What do I have to do to graduate and get my diploma?
Here is what we know for seniors:
Senior Projects and Essential Skills are suspended this year. You do not have to complete your Senior Project, however there may be an opportunity to showcase your project if you choose to do so.
All credit requirements for graduation are the same. 
If you were passing your classes on March 13, the last day of in-person school, you will receive credit for those classes and a grade of pass. Those credits count toward graduation requirements. 
High School and Catalyst staff will look at every seniors grades and credits and contact everyone no later than April 30.

DOCS_modelChunk = [{"ty":"is","ibi":20610,"s":"If you were failing a class as of March 13, and/or you do not have enough credits to graduate even with the classes you were in this semester, we will create a way for you to make up the work and/or earn other credit. High School and Catalyst staff will develop a plan for you and contact you no later than April 30.

Q. Do seniors have to participate in Distance Learning for All?
If seniors are sure they were passing their classes on March 13, and know they have enough credits to graduate, they are not required to participate in Distance Learning for All. We highly encourage students to stay engaged in their learning. Here are some reasons why you still might choose to participate:
You arent sure if you were passing on March 13. Participating in Distance Learning for All will make it easier to bring your grade to passing.
You are part of an Advanced Placement (AP) class. These classes will continue to cover material that may help you pass the AP test and help you earn college credit.
You are part of a Dual Credit class. In order to earn the college credit you have already done a lot of work for, you must continue in these classes. If you stop, you will still earn your high school diploma, but you will not earn college credit.
You want to continue learning and preparing yourself for post-secondary options, and enjoy participating with your friends! You can continue to be part of these classes.

Q. Can I still get a Chromebook or help with internet access? I thought my device would work but this is more than I thought.
While the district-wide distribution at the high school is ended, you can contact your school and they can work with you to get the equipment you need.

Q. Students havent used online video conferences like Google Meets. What should students be thinking about?
Meetings in video chat conferences are a new experience for many of us. Students can be successful by doing the following things:

Check in with your teacher. Gather your materials. 
Be on time. Check in through the chat function when you arrive.
Stay engaged. Nod or give a thumbs up if others are talking.
Mute your mic if youre not speaking.
Use the chat or raise hand function to ask questions and share ideas.
Wait for the teacher to call on you or unmute your mic.
Take notes in a doc or on paper for reference.
If using video, look at the camera and not the screen.

Students, be reminded that the dress code applies to online video chats, and students should act with the same respect that would be expected in the classroom.

Q. What are other guidelines for the Google Meet help sessions with teachers?
These sessions are designed for these types of things:
Time for students who want help from a teacher on assigned work
Multiple students working together on similar tasks
A time to ask for help and guidance on academics
An opportunity for the teacher to reteach concepts if needed
Flexible (students can attend the entire 30 minutes or just stay until their question is answered)
A time for teachers to check in with students

These sessions are NOT:
Social time for students to chat with each other
Parent-teacher conversations
Required for each student

Q. How will my student get their things from their lockers and desks?
We are preparing a plan for this. We will develop a system that protects against the spread of the virus and provide an opportunity to collect the students personal things. We will communicate to you in the coming days when we have finalized our plan.
 
Q. What if I cant remember my login or password?
If you dont have your login or password, call your school building for assistance.
 
Q. Is school canceled for the rest of the year?
On April 8, Governor Kate Brown announced that schools are to remain closed for in-person classes for the rest of this school year. While this news isnt completely unexpected, hearing the official word makes the grief of all the losses for our students, especially our graduating seniors, very hard.

Life with the Stay at Home order is something most of us have never experienced before. Many are dealing with uncertainties about jobs and income, about housing and food, not to mention figuring out how to juggle all of those things while caring for children and nurturing their education. But we can do this together as a community. Teachers and staff have been hard at work preparing to start Distance Learning for All next Monday, April 13.
 
Q. What about graduation ceremonies? Will they occur or be rescheduled or canceled? 
We do not know at this time. It will all depend on the governors orders and whether the spread of this virus can be slowed or contained. We will follow all state guidance.
 
Q. Are students going to have to repeat this years grade level? 
No. We will be adjusting our work at the beginning of next year in all grades to make sure we can provide the supports necessary for your students to receive the grade level content, skills, and standards they need by the end of next year. 
 
Q. What about annual state testing? 
We have been informed Oregon has received a conditional waiver from the Federal government to not administer state testing this year.
 
Q. What about forecasting/scheduling classes for next year? 
We are working on online options for this and will communicate as we have the system and process in place.
 
Q. What about Kindergarten registration scheduled for Tuesday April 7? 
This is canceled due to the school closure. We are working on alternate ways of registering and will communicate as soon as possible.

Q. I paid an athletic fee for a spring sport. Can I receive a refund?
Yes. The high school athletic department is already at work to determine who paid fees and needs a refund. If there are no other debts on your student account, you will receive a refund in the mail next week. 

The leaders of the Disneyland trip are working on what parts of funding can be rolled over to next year, and what can be refunded. You will be contacted when they work out those details. 

Q. Are there going to be make up days added on to the school year? How will this affect graduation and other events for seniors? 
It is too early to know how many make up days will be needed, or when they will occur, or how they might affect graduation or other events for seniors. The state may change their guidance. We are unable to make any definitive statement about how this will affect the end of school.




Older questions:
Q. I need a device and/or internet access for my student to work on school work. How do I get one?
Follow this link, and fill out the request form: https://bit.ly/3bvclVV Youll see links to English and Spanish versions of the form. 
 
Q. When can I pick up the device Ive requested?
You can pick up a Chromebook at Newberg High School at the following times:

Internet hotspots to provide internet access at home will be available for pick up starting on Wednesday April 8 and for the rest of the week.

Directions:
Drive in through the south entrance (Elliot St. lot). Pull forward, turn left and stop alongside the curb near the school. Do not exit your vehicle. A staff member will come to your car to bring a device and collect your information. When you pick up your device, you will receive a paper copy with instructions for how to get started on the Chromebook. It is also available here: https://bit.ly/2XemP8z 

You may exit using the same Elliott St. exit. We look forward to seeing you! Thank you for wanting to stay engaged with your learning.

Q. Can I just show up and pick up a device at one of the times listed above?
Yes. It is helpful if you can fill out the form beforehand, but you can just show up if needed. Please be patient as staff works through your request.

Q. Can I request a device so my student doesnt have to share?
Yes. Many families have a family device, but with the move to Distance Learning for All, you may now realize you need a device for each of your students. Go ahead and request a device.

Q. When will you have help for accessing internet?
Internet hotspots to provide internet access at home will be available for pick up starting on Wednesday April 8 and for the rest of the week. You can pick them up at the high school as described above.

If you already have internet access and are experiencing technical difficulties, please email support@newberg.k12.or.us or call 503-554-4545.

Q. I already picked up a device, but it isnt working/has damage. What should I do?
We apologize! Please bring the device to the high school at one of the times listed above and we will swap it out for a different one.
 
Q. I cannot come to pick up a device. Can you deliver it?
We will work on a delivery system the week of April 6 to get devices to those who requested a device but did not pick one up during these times. You will receive a call if your requested device is not picked up.

Q. When will supplemental educational materials be available? How will we access them?
We are excited to roll out some optional supplemental educational resources that you can use at home. Our teachers have developed simple, creative experiences, organized by grade and subject area. They arent required and wont be used for grading, but they are an excellent way for students to stay engaged in learning during this school closure.

We see these supplemental educational resources as a good way to lead into the additional material that is coming. The district is currently developing additional content and learning experiences as part of Distance Learning for All, which will begin rolling out on April 13. We will communicate more as that date gets closer. You can get used to coming to this page as a starting place for all future learning resources as we expand.

Here is the link: http://bit.do/newberg It is also accessible from the district website, using the button that says Learning Resources.

Q. I have further questions about these supplemental educational resources. Where do I go for help?
First, check the At Home Learning FAQ: https://bit.ly/2wNCv80 
If that doesnt answer your question, email support@newberg.k12.or.us or call 503-554-4545.
 
Q. Yesterday you talked about Distance Learning for All. When will that begin? My student wont come to school, will they?
Distance Learning for All will begin on Monday April 13. This will be a combination of online resources, video resources, physical resources, and video or audio chats at certain times with a licensed staff member. Everything will be designed to work in partnership with families and caregivers and done from the home, as the governors closure of schools is still in effect. 
 
We will be giving lots more information in the weeks ahead.

Q. Why havent you provided online access to educational materials? When will you move school online?
We continue to work to make sure every student without a device and/or reliable internet has the ability to connect to the communication and resources we are creating. (If you have a need, click here and fill out the form: https://bit.ly/3bvclVV)
 
We are being directed to move to Distance Learning for All and to begin implementation on April 13. 
 
This change was not unanticipated. Last week, our district team began planning for Phase 2 of Remote Learning. But know that behind the scenes, weve been working hard over the last two weeks to prepare our systems to deliver remote learning for all our students during an extended closure.
 
This will be a brand new model that we will create together, and we will prioritize equity in every decision. Its going to be a challenge! But I believe our talented staff will rise to this occasion for our students. We will innovate and build, improving what we do each step of the way. We will partner with families and caregivers to ensure safety and wellness for our students, foster connections and relationships, and center on equity.
 
ODEs guidance is broad at this point; we expect each day to bring new information. Distance Learning for All will include a regular, daily connection with a licensed staff member; a focus on relevant, essential, standards-based learning; teachers, families, and caregivers working as a team to establish learning routines; and teachers reporting on and monitoring each students progress toward learning goals and standards.

Q. How is my senior going to graduate? What about senior projects and essential skills? 
ODE announced finalized graduation requirements on April 8 to give our seniors a path to graduation. More details will come later, but essentially it is this: if you were on track to graduate and passing your classes when schools closed on March 13, you will receive a passing grade for the rest of the year and earn that credit and graduate. If you were failing any classes, you will receive an incomplete. We will be working on specific ways for students to pass classes in which they receive an incomplete, and/or to earn credits still needed to meet the graduation requirements. High school and Catalyst staff will review every single senior, evaluate where they are and what is still needed, and communicate with them and their families by April 30 with an individualized plan. Senior projects and other essential skills are suspended and do not need to be completed in order to graduate this year. There are still unanswered questions about how this all will apply to students that are not seniors, but those answers are yet to come from the ODE and we will communicate with you as soon as we learn more.
 
Q. What about my freshman/sophomore/junior who may miss out on earning credits this year? This closure could hurt their ability to graduate on time. 
ODE has promised that the next priority after figuring things out for this years seniors is to address the needs of other high school students. We will work with every student for their success in high school as we learn what the guidance is from ODE.

Q. I do not have internet access at home. Do you have any resources?
The Internet Essentials program is offering free internet for two months for families who are eligible for public assistance programs such as the National School Lunch Program, Housing Assistance, Medicaid, SNAP, SSI and others. More information found here: https://www.internetessentials.com/covid19 

We know some students and families do not have access to our communications or other resources because they need a device and/or internet access at their home. If you would like to request to borrow a device and/or need internet access, you can request it with this form. Please assist others who may need this and cant see online communication, offering to fill out the form for them if they dont have a way to do so. We will also be calling students and families after spring break, but wanted to make the form available to those who can access it now: 
English: bit.do/npsdevices 
Espaol: bit.do/npsdispositivos

Q. Have there been any confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Newberg School District?
Not at this time. We are in regular contact with Yamhill County Public Health, who will inform us if there is a confirmed case of a student or staff member. We will follow all local and state health authority directions.

Oregon Health Authority information page on the Coronavirus: http://bit.ly/2IbZoDT

Q. Who is at risk for COVID-19?
Currently, the risk to the general public is low. To minimize the risk of spread, health officials are working with healthcare providers to promptly identify and evaluate any suspected cases. Travelers to and from certain areas of the world may be at increased risk. See wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel for the latest travel guidance from the CDC. Current research also suggests that children are least likely to get COVID-19, possibly because they experience a great number of mild coronaviruses, which helps bolster their immune system. People between 30 and 79 are most likely to contract the virus, and older individuals with compromised immune systems and/or who have a history of smoking are most at risk of dying from the virus. 

Q. What are the symptoms of COVID-19?
Fever, cough, difficulty breathing. If you have symptoms, call your healthcare provider to identify the safest way to receive care. Let them know if you have traveled to an affected area or come in contact with an ill person who has traveled to an affected area within the last 14 days.

Q. How can I prevent getting COVID-19?
If you are traveling overseas (to China or Italy, but also to other places), follow the CDCs guidance: wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel. Right now, COVID-19 has not been spreading widely in the United States, so there are no additional precautions recommended for the general public. Steps you can take to prevent the spread of flu and the common cold will also help prevent COVID-19:
wash hands often with soap and water. If not available, use hand sanitizer
avoid touching your eyes, nose, or mouth with unwashed hands
avoid contact with people who are sick
stay home while you are sick and avoid close contact with others
cover your mouth and nose with a tissue or sleeve when coughing or sneezing
Currently, there are no vaccines available to prevent COVID-19 infections.

Q. I dont feel safe having my child at school. How can I get work for my student?

Teachers and counselors will work with the parent/guardian of any student who is confirmed with COVID-19, is under quarantine from a medical provider, or has a medical alert of a compromised immune system, to provide education as long as needed. This would most likely involve uploading work and lessons online or providing it at schools for relatives to retrieve. We ask for your patience as teachers develop this work in addition to their normal duties.

When families choose to remove students as a preventive measure and they are not as described in the paragraph above (i.e. they dont have symptoms themselves and/or they do not have a documented medical need), the Oregon Department of Education requires us to unenroll the student after ten school days. When students return to school, they will be re-enrolled.

Students who are out for other sickness of a shorter duration than 10 days will receive make-up work when they return.

Q. My student isnt feeling well. How should I determine whether to send to school?

Do not attend school with a fever higher than 100.4. Students may return after being fever free (without fever-reducing medication) for 24 hours.
Do not attend school with any unexplained vomiting episode. Students may return 24 hours after the last episode. 
Do not attend school if experiencing diarrhea (three or more unexplained episodes of watery or loose stools in 24 hours OR sudden onset of loose stools). Students may return 24 hours after the last episode.
Do not attend school if experiencing serious, sustained coughing, shortness of breath, or difficulty breathing.
Do not attend school if experiencing a new rash accompanied by a feverstudents may return after the rash goes away or clearance is given by a health care provider.
Do not attend school if experiencing drainage from a sore that cannot be contained within a bandage OR sores that are increasing in size OR new sores developing day-to-day.
Do not attend school if experiencing symptoms that prevent active participation in usual school activities OR student is requiring more care than school can safely provide.

Q. Are you going to cancel field trips/extracurricular activities?
Updated March 11, 2020: Governor Brown issued new guidance March 11, 2020. Accordingly, all non-essential school activities are suspended for 30 days, effective March 12, 2020. This includes all school-based assemblies and events, off-campus field trips, parent meetings, and professional development meetings and events.

Q. What about Chehalem Valley Middle Schools planned trip to Wadayama, Japan?
After consulting with our hosts in Japan and with health authorities, the District has made the decision to not send students to Wadayama this year, postponing until next school year.

Q. What about the NHS Performing Arts trip to Disneyland?
Updated March 11, 2020: In accordance with new guidance from Governor Brown on March 11, 2020, the trip to Disneyland is suspended.

Q. What cleaning protocols and infection control measures does the District in place?
Building custodians are implementing an enhanced disinfecting plan, effective immediately. This includes daily cleaning of high touch point areas.

Custodians use E23 (an EPA approved disinfectant), towels, and disposable gloves that they use for interim cleaning. Students are NOT to do any cleaning.

Soap and water washing is the best prevention, and washing areas are regularly restocked with soap and paper towels. 15 cases of hand sanitizer are on order to be distributed to needed areas. 

Facial tissues are available at each school as well (if classrooms run out, they can request more from their custodian).

The floor wax used throughout the district this year contains an anti-microbial that is designed to kill germs.

Buses are being sprayed with bleach water or Lysol on a daily basis. 

Staff are reinforcing expectations around hand washing, covering coughs and/or sneezes, and staying home when students feel ill. 

Q. Will you tell me if I or my child has been exposed to COVID-19?
People who are at risk for exposure to COVID-19 because of known contact with an ill person will be contacted by the Yamhill County Public Health Departments Incident Management Team (IMT). If you are concerned about your risk from a potential exposure, you can also self-assess using the CDCs Guidance for Risk Assessment. Because of HIPPA restrictions, the school/District is unable to share information regarding specific individuals. 

Q. What specific steps is the Newberg School District taking to prevent cases of COVID-19 and what would you do if a case of COVID-19 is confirmed in a student, staff member, parent, or family member?
Currently, there are no immunizations available for COVID-19. However, getting a seasonal flu vaccine is still recommended, as is following good health habits:
get plenty of rest 
drink lots of fluids
eat a healthy diet
cover your mouth and nose if you cough or sneeze, dispose of used tissues, and wash your hands frequently
avoid contact with people who are sick
stay home if you are sick
Confirmed cases of COVID-19 will be managed by the Yamhill County Health Department and we will take direction from them. Most likely, persons with the virus and any family members who have been in close contact with the person will be asked to quarantine themselves. Additional cleaning would take place within the school, and the District would consult with the Yamhill County Public Health Department for any further recommended steps. 

Should the Yamhill County Health Department direct us to close a school or schools, we will notify parents, guardians, staff, and community by email from the District Office, on the Districts website, on District Social Media, and on the District mobile phone app. If you see a social media post from another source that says school is closed, please check official District channels to confirm before spreading that news.

Q. What is your plan for continuing students education if there is a mass spread of COVID-19 in the Newberg School District?
We are currently considering options for this scenario and will share additional information as it is available. One issue to work through is that not all families have access to the internet at their homes. In the event of a school closure, we do not believe we can provide an equitable educational experience to all students, as we are required by law to do. We would establish make-up days for the closure.

Q. Can my child wear a mask to school as a preventative measure?
We ask that people do not wear masks in our schools unless they have been advised to do so by a healthcare professional. There are several reasons for this:
Wearing a mask simply as a precaution creates unnecessary concern in the school environment and potentially exposes students to bullying and/or harassment. 
Students are likely to adjust their mask frequently throughout the day, which causes them to touch their face more than they normally would and generate additional risk of disease transmission.
Masks are needed for those who are ill, healthcare workers, and others who may be caring for an ill person. To ensure masks are available for those people, healthy people are not advised to wear masks.

Q. How is COVID-19 treated?
There are no medications specifically approved for COVID-19. Most people with mild COVID-19 illness will recover on their own by drinking plenty of fluids, resting, and taking pain and fever medications. However, some cases develop pneumonia and require medical care or hospitalization. 

Q. Where can I get additional information about COVID-19?
If you have specific questions, you can call the statewide helpline at 2-1-1 or your healthcare provider. The Oregon Health Authoritys COVID-19 website, healthoregon.gov/coronavirus also has updated information. 



April 15 update:
Hello everyone,

Thank you for all the ways youre learning and figuring out how to implement Distance Learning for All! Its our first week, and we are all figuring out logins and access and what to do. We will keep improving, and keep working to make it possible for all of our students to keep learning!

Even with all the newness, we are pleased with the start of Distance Learning for All. In middle and high school, more than 80% of our students have logged into Google Classroom for at least 30 minutes. In elementary schools, weve seen at least 75% of our students connect through Clever, our online portal...and Edwards Elementary is in the lead with 79%! Thanks to our secretaries, teachers and tech support team who have gone the extra mile to make connections with our students. 

Here is our biggest encouragement to all the students and families making your way through this new normal: take a deep breath, do as much as you can, and know that our goal for Distance Learning for All is only to help, and not harm in any way. Our teachers are working together to concentrate on the most essential standards, the most important things youll need to learn as you move on to the next grade. We cant do it all, but we can cover essentials. When were all back together in person, we will work hard together to make up ground and move forward. 

Heres some information you may be wondering:

Q. I dont know what my child is supposed to be doing. Its hard to keep track of all the emails from teachers. Is there one spot that can give me an overview?
Yes! Our teachers have created overview templates for the week, to share the goals and objectives and the activities to do. Its all organized by grade and subject.

Youll still need to login to Google Classroom or SeeSaw to get the activities, but these overviews are in English and Spanish to help parents, guardians, and caregivers have an easy way to find what is happening for the week: https://bit.ly/2XD6wST 

Q. I still need help getting all this to work. Where do I go?
Begin with your students teacher. Send them an email with your question. You can also use the Technology Resource page with answers to many tech questions: https://bit.ly/3cmRy7D 

Q. Can I still get a Chromebook or internet access at home?
While the district-wide distribution at the high school is ended, you can contact your school and they can work with you to get the equipment you need.

Students, be reminded that the dress code applies to online video chats, and students should act with the same respect that would be expected in the classroom.

Q. Will the Distance Learning for All work be graded?
Grading is proving very complicated to make sure it is done in an equitable way. We want to evaluate based on learning of standards, not on access to the learning or access to the technology. We want students engaged in learning, while keeping anxiety about performance as low as possible.

The Oregon Department of Education (ODE) has not yet released complete guidance for grading. They have indicated that for grades 6-12, students will receive a grade of pass or incomplete, based on the entire semester. Teachers will be evaluating and selecting the key standards that need to be demonstrated as proficient in order to receive a passing grade. Evidence for those standards can be from either the in-person class time before March 13, or during Distance Learning for All. This semester will not affect a students cumulative GPA.

If a student receives an incomplete grade because certain key standards were not demonstrated, they will have the opportunity to demonstrate proficiency either this spring or summer, or again when we return in the fall. When proficiency is demonstrated, the grade for this semester will be changed to pass. A grade of incomplete will not affect promotion to the next grade level during this unique situation. In middle school or high school, it may affect which course a student is placed in when we return to in-person learning.

For most students, not including the semester in the cumulative GPA is helpful. For some students who were hoping to raise their GPA to qualify for the Oregon Promise credit for college, there may be anxiety. The Office of Student Access and Completion (OSAC) has said they will provide a way for our high school registrar to indicate that it was mathematically possible for a student to have raised their cumulative, unweighted GPA to 2.50 if grades had been given this semester instead of pass/incomplete. This will qualify a student for Oregon Promise. Our high school staff will be contacting every senior no later than April 30 with details about graduation requirements and these types of GPA issues.

ODE has not yet given indication for how we are to handle Elementary progress marks. Please know our goal is for students to be engaged in learning, while keeping anxiety about performance as low as possible.

Q. Our family income has changed. Can I get help with food?
Yes! Anyone 18 years old or younger can pick up a grab-and-go breakfast and lunch at any of our food distribution sites: https://bit.ly/2Jk8kHS 

Also, many may now qualify for free/reduced meals through the Federal Government. We want students to have their food needs met. We encourage you to fill out the form now, and it will continue to qualify you through next school year: https://bit.ly/3abwvDz 

Q. My student needs to get their things from their desk and locker. When will that happen?
We are working on a system that will safely allow students to get their things and maintain healthy cleaning and social distancing guidelines. We will let you know when this can occur.

Q. I paid an athletic fee for a spring sport. Can I receive a refund?
Yes. The high school athletic department is already at work to determine who paid fees and needs a refund. If there are no other debts on your student account, you will receive a refund in the mail next week. 

The leaders of the Disneyland trip are working on what parts of funding can be rolled over to next year, and what can be refunded. You will be contacted when they work out those details. 

Thank you, and have a good day.


April 10 update:
To the families of Dundee and Newberg Public Schools,

We have a lot of information for you today, and hope this will answer a lot of your questions as you prepare for Distance Learning for All on Monday, April 13. We know there are still some unanswered questions. Know that we will keep communicating as we learn more answers in the days and weeks ahead.

Q. What are the goals of Distance Learning for All?
We want to help students keep learning. We want to help students make progress on important educational standards that prepare them for future learning and for life. We want students to be as prepared as possible when we do return to in-person schooling, which we hope will be next fall.

Distance Learning for All will not replace all the education that would have happened if we continued school in-person. And, we do not want to create a bunch of work to just keep students busy. Our teachers are doing hard work to focus on essential standards that are the key building blocks for future learning. We will improve each week, and we expect to get better at this new adventure as we go along!

We know parents, guardians, and caregivers arent trained as teachers and have other responsibilities, and we are creating materials to be as easy to use as possible. Q. What kinds of things will students be doing?
It will vary depending on the grade level. Generally, all students will have about two lessons per week in each subject/class. Lessons are designed to be completed at your own pace and on your own schedule through the week. Each lesson is designed to take roughly 30 minutes, varying by grade level and subject. 

Each teacher at the secondary level (middle and high school) will also schedule video conference sessions in Google Meets where students will participate at the same time as other students. These face-to-face times over the internet will be used for help sessions and for connecting with students to see how they are doing. Attendance in these sessions is not required, but they are intended as a way to provide support to students and families in their distance learning work. 

Teachers are working together across the district to create consistent lessons by grade and subject. This means, for example, that you might have a video in your classroom from a different teacher than you are used to. You can be sure that your teacher was part of the group that planned the material you are learning from.

Your individual school and your teachers will be giving more specific information. We know there will be lots to learn and lots of questions. We are here to learn from each other and to help. You can contact your teacher or your school for assistance. Know that we wish we could be together face-to-face, but we are doing this for everyones health and safety in this time of a pandemic.

Q. How will students access their work?
Most students will use Google Classroom to access all their assignments and resources. Google Classroom is a Learning Management System that organizes lessons, videos, links, and other resources into individual assignments and units. For many students, Google Classroom is very familiar, while some others may be using it for the first time. Grades 3-12 will almost all be using Google Classroom.

Kindergarten through 2nd grade students will get their assignments and resources from their teacher in SeeSaw. Some of our elementary classrooms were already using SeeSaw as a way to share what was happening at school with people at home. This will expand that use. Some will be familiar with it, while for others it will be brand new.

Students, your school email address will be essential to use during this time of Distance Learning. Communication from your teachers will be to that address, and you will use that account to login to resources. We know some students, especially elementary students, may never have used that account. Parents/Guardians can call your school to get the login information for your student. 

Q. How can parents know what is going on? How can parents support their students?
Similar to what we did with the Supplemental Educational Materials, parents can go to the District website and click a grade or subject. You will find lesson descriptions, support for at-home learning, tech support, and some basic instructions for the week: http://bit.do/newberg. 

These lesson overviews will be in both English and Spanish. To actually access and complete the assignments and activities, students and/or parents will need to login to Google Classroom or SeeSaw, depending on the grade of the student. 

Parents can also support by helping students maintain a basic daily schedule for learning. All of us are out of routine, and that in itself creates anxiety. We encourage parents to make a simple schedule for learning and other fun.

Q. What is the suggested daily schedule for students?
Everyone will be a little different, depending on work schedules at home, grade level, individual class schedules, etc. But here are some rough ideas for what it could look like:

For Elementary students

Each day will have a different focus:
Mondays and Wednesdays - Humanities (Literacy and Social Studies), PE/Health
Tuesdays and Thursdays - Math, Science, Music

For Middle and High School Students:

Middle and High School students will focus on different periods on different days. Monday: Periods 1 and 2. Tuesday: Periods 3 and 4. Wednesday: Periods 5 and 6. Thursday: Period 7. Friday: Social Emotional Learning (SEL). (Catalyst students have a different schedule and should refer to communication from your school.)

Q. I need help with Google Classroom and/or SeeSaw.
We will include help for accessing both Google Classroom and SeeSaw in the resources section on the District website. Go to http://bit.do/newberg and look for the Student/Family Tech Support page on the Learning Resource Site. Or click here: https://bit.ly/2xjUkvt 

Q. My student is on an IEP. How will you support my student?
In several ways. Special Education teachers are part of the teams creating lessons, and are working to include elements in the lessons that support all students. Special Education teachers are also working hard on an individual basis for each student to meet needs. Staff will be in contact with you for support. Case managers will be scheduling meetings and rescheduling missed meetings. Also, please take a look at our district page at http://bit.do/newberg for Special Education Resources and Activities for students.

Q. My student needs English Language Development support. How will you support my student?
In several ways. EL teachers are part of the teams creating lessons, and are working to include elements in lessons that support all students. EL teachers will also be connecting with students to provide support and meet student needs.

Q. Is this Distance Learning for All required?
We expect our students to participate, and are continuing to work on removing barriers so that all students are able to participate.

Q. What about seniors? What do I have to do to graduate and get my diploma?
Here is what we know for seniors:
Senior Projects and Essential Skills are suspended this year. You do not have to complete your Senior Project, however there may be an opportunity to showcase your project if you choose to do so.
All credit requirements for graduation are the same. 
If you were passing your classes on March 13, the last day of in-person school, you will receive credit for those classes and a grade of pass. Those credits count toward graduation requirements. 
High School and Catalyst staff will look at every seniors grades and credits and contact everyone no later than April 30.
If you were failing a class as of March 13, and/or you do not have enough credits to graduate even with the classes you were in this semester, we will create a way for you to make up the work and/or earn other credit. High School and Catalyst staff will develop a plan for you and contact you no later than April 30.

DOCS_modelChunk = [{"ty":"is","ibi":61730,"s":"If seniors are sure they were passing their classes on March 13, and know they have enough credits to graduate, they are not required to participate in Distance Learning for All. We highly encourage students to stay engaged in their learning. Here are some reasons why you still might choose to participate:
You arent sure if you were passing on March 13. Participating in Distance Learning for All will make it easier to bring your grade to passing.
You are part of an Advanced Placement (AP) class. These classes will continue to cover material that may help you pass the AP test and help you earn college credit.
You are part of a Dual Credit class. In order to earn the college credit you have already done a lot of work for, you must continue in these classes. If you stop, you will still earn your high school diploma, but you will not earn college credit.
You want to continue learning and preparing yourself for post-secondary options, and enjoy participating with your friends! You can continue to be part of these classes.

Q. Can I still get a Chromebook or help with internet access? I thought my device would work but this is more than I thought.
Yes! Please follow this link and fill out the request form (in either English or Spanish): https://bit.ly/3bvclVV 

You can pick up your requested device at Newberg High School on Monday, April 13 from 3:00 pm 6:00 pm. After that, we will find other ways to distribute requested devices.

Directions:
Drive in through the south entrance (Elliot St. lot). Pull forward, turn left and stop alongside the curb near the school. Do not exit your vehicle. A staff member will come to your car to bring a device and collect your information. When you pick up your device, you will receive a paper copy with instructions for how to get started on the Chromebook. It is also available here: https://bit.ly/2XemP8z 

You may exit using the same Elliott St. exit. We look forward to seeing you! Thank you for wanting to stay engaged with your learning.

Q. Students havent used online video conferences like Google Meets. What should students be thinking about?
Meetings in video chat conferences are a new experience for many of us. Students can be successful by doing the following things:

Check in with your teacher. Gather your materials. 
Be on time. Check in through the chat function when you arrive.
Stay engaged. Nod or give a thumbs up if others are talking.
Mute your mic if youre not speaking.
Use the chat or raise hand function to ask questions and share ideas.
Wait for the teacher to call on you or unmute your mic.
Take notes in a doc or on paper for reference.
If using video, look at the camera and not the screen.

Q. What are other guidelines for the Google Meet help sessions with teachers?
These sessions are designed for these types of things:
Time for students who want help from a teacher on assigned work
Multiple students working together on similar tasks
A time to ask for help and guidance on academics
An opportunity for the teacher to reteach concepts if needed
Flexible (students can attend the entire 30 minutes or just stay until their question is answered)
A time for teachers to check in with students

These sessions are NOT:
Social time for students to chat with each other
Parent-teacher conversations
Required for each student

Q. How will my student get their things from their lockers and desks?
We are preparing a plan for this. We will develop a system that protects against the spread of the virus and provide an opportunity to collect the students personal things. We will communicate to you in the coming days when we have finalized our plan.

Thanks for your partnership as we work together to help all our students! Have a good weekend, and we will begin this new adventure on Monday.

From the whole district team at Newberg Public Schools,

Gregg Koskela, Nikki Fowler, Derek Brown, Ann Ziehl, Luke Neff, Karen Pugsley, Shanna Andres, Joe Morelock

April 8 update:
A message from the Superintendent

To the families of Dundee and Newberg Public Schools,

Today, Governor Kate Brown and State Superintendent Colt Gill held a news conference to announce that schools are to remain closed for in-person classes for the rest of this school year. While this news isnt completely unexpected, hearing the official word makes the grief of all the losses for our students, especially our graduating seniors, very hard.

Life with the Stay at Home order is something most of us have never experienced before. Many are dealing with uncertainties about jobs and income, about housing and food, not to mention figuring out how to juggle all of those things while caring for children and nurturing their education. Finding out it will extend through the rest of the school year is challenging.

But we can do this together as a community. Teachers and staff have been hard at work preparing to start Distance Learning for All next Monday, April 13. We will have more specific information for you later this week, and we are doing our best to provide families with the resources and support you need to continue each students education. We continue to serve more than 1,300 meals a day to students who need them, through 16 pick-up sites and through delivery to the homes of those who cannot get to a site. We have distributed almost 2,000 Chromebooks to families, and today we began distributing internet hotspots to those who do not have internet access at home. Our teachers and staff have been making contact with students, making sure we know their needs and working on solutions. We have some work ahead to develop a safe process for students to get their personal things from the school building, and will communicate that when we have it in place.

The Oregon Department of Education (ODE) also announced finalized graduation requirements today to give our seniors a path to graduation. More details will come later, but essentially it is this: if you were on track to graduate and passing your classes when schools closed on March 13, you will receive a passing grade for the rest of the year and earn that credit and graduate. If you were failing any classes, you will receive an incomplete. We will be working on specific ways for students to pass classes in which they receive an incomplete, and/or to earn credits still needed to meet the graduation requirements. High school and Catalyst staff will review every single senior, evaluate where they are and what is still needed, and communicate with them and their families by April 30 with an individualized plan. Senior projects and other essential skills are suspended and do not need to be completed in order to graduate this year. There are still unanswered questions about how this all will apply to students that are not seniors, but those answers are yet to come from the ODE and we will communicate with you as soon as we learn more.

This is a challenge for us all. We miss doing what we love to do. But we are going to make it together, and Im proud of what we are accomplishing. Stay safe, stay healthy.

Sincerely,

Dr. Joe Morelock
Superintendent
Newberg Public Schools

We know some students and families do not have access to our communications or other educational resources because they need a device and/or internet access at their home. If you would like to request to borrow a device and/or need internet access, you can request it with this form.

You may exit using the same Elliott St. exit. We look forward to seeing you! Thank you for wanting to stay engaged with your learning.

Can I just show up and pick up a device at one of the times listed above?
Yes. It is helpful if you can fill out the form beforehand, but you can just show up if needed. Please be patient as staff works through your request.

Can I request a device so my student doesnt have to share?
Yes. Many families have a family device, but with the move to Distance Learning for All, you may now realize you need a device for each of your students. Go ahead and request a device.

When will you have help for accessing internet?
Internet hotspots to provide internet access at home will be available for pick up starting on Wednesday April 8 and for the rest of the week. You can pick them up at the high school as described above.

If you already have internet access and are experiencing technical difficulties, please email support@newberg.k12.or.us or call 503-554-4545.

I already picked up a device, but it isnt working/has damage. What should I do?
We apologize! Please bring the device to the high school at one of the times listed above and we will swap it out for a different one.


April 2 update:
Hello families of Newberg and Dundee,

We are excited to roll out some optional supplemental educational resources that you can use at home. Our teachers have developed simple, creative experiences, organized by grade and subject area. They arent required and wont be used for grading, but they are an excellent way for students to stay engaged in learning during this school closure.

We see these supplemental educational resources as a good way to lead into the additional material that is coming. The district is currently developing additional content and learning experiences as part of Distance Learning for All, which will begin rolling out on April 13. We will communicate more as that date gets closer. You can get used to coming to this page as a starting place for all future learning resources as we expand.

How do I get these materials?
Here is the link: http://bit.do/newberg It is also accessible from the district website, using the button that says Learning Resources.

Some things are asking me for a login. How do I get that information?
If you dont have your login or password, call your school building for assistance. School phones are being forwarded, and generally are answered from 8 am 3 pm. You can leave a voicemail if needed.

I have further questions about these supplemental educational resources. Where do I go for help?
First, check the At Home Learning FAQ: https://bit.ly/2wNCv80 
If that doesnt answer your question, email support@newberg.k12.or.us or call 503-554-4545.

Thank you!

Gregg Koskela 
Communications and Community Relations Coordinator
Newberg Public Schools


April 1 update:
To our Newberg and Dundee families,
 
Todays update has some questions and answers.
 
Q. I need a device and/or internet access for my student to work on school work. How do I get one?
Follow this link, and fill out the request form: https://bit.ly/3bvclVV Youll see links to English and Spanish versions of the form. Do not come to pick up a device without filling out a form. 
 
Q. Can I request a device so my student doesnt have to share?
Yes. Many families have a family device, but with the move to Distance Learning for All, you may now realize you need a device for each of your students. Go ahead and request a device using this form: https://bit.ly/3bvclVV
 
Q. I requested a device already. When can I pick it up?
We are loaning out Chromebooks for all student requests. No iPads will be distributed. Staff have been cleaning them all this week. To avoid congregating and to maintain social distance, we will distribute the devices on the following schedule on a drive-up basis at Newberg High School:
 
Thursday, April 2nd
8:00 - 11:00 am K-5 students with last name A-L
12:00 - 3:00 pm Grades 6-12 students will last name A-L

Friday, April 3rd
8:00 - 11:00 am K-5 students with last name M-Z
12:00 - 3:00 pm Grades 6-12 students will last name M-Z
 
Directions:
Drive in through the south entrance (Elliot St. lot). Pull forward, turn left and stop alongside the curb near the school. Do not exit your vehicle. A staff member will come to your car to bring a device and collect your information. When you pick up your device, you will receive a paper copy with Frequently Asked Questions. You may exit using the same Elliott St. exit. We look forward to seeing you! Thank you for wanting to stay engaged with your learning.
 
Q. What if I cannot pick up my device during the assigned time?
Please do your best to come during the assigned time. If you cannot make it, you may come to one of the other sessions. Devices will also be available the week of April 6. We will make them available when we distribute the internet hotspots. More details to come.
 
Q. I requested internet access already. When will I have help with that?
We have purchased internet hotspots from two different cell carriers, in order to provide the best possible service where you physically live. Please be sure to fill out a request form with your physical address. These devices were ordered weeks ago, but just recently arrived and are being configured to work with our school network. They will be available for pick up during the week of April 6. More details to come.
 
Q. I cannot come to pick up a device. Can you deliver it?
We will work on a delivery system the week of April 6 to get devices to those who requested a device but did not pick one up during these times. You will receive a call if your requested device is not picked up.
 
Q. What if I cant remember my login or password?
If you dont have your login or password, call your school building for assistance.
 
Q. When will supplemental educational materials be available? How will we access them?
The materials will be available with a link from our website on Thursday, April 2.
 
Q. Yesterday you talked about Distance Learning for All. When will that begin? My student wont come to school, will they?
Distance Learning for All will begin on Monday April 13. This will be a combination of online resources, video resources, physical resources, and video or audio chats at certain times with a licensed staff member. Everything will be designed to work in partnership with families and caregivers and done from the home, as the governors closure of schools is still in effect. 
 
We will be giving lots more information in the weeks ahead.
 
Q. Does this mean school is canceled for the rest of the year?
At this time, the governor has closed schools through April 28. President Trump has also issued a stay at home order through April 30. We will abide by all government directives. Colt Gill, Oregons State Superintendent of Schools, has said there is a very real potential that our students, like in many other states, may not return to school this academic year.
 
Q. Are more food distribution sites now open?
Yes! Any person 18 years or younger can pick up two grab-and-go meals (breakfast and lunch) at 16 different sites. More details here: https://bit.ly/2X19DU8
 
We will communicate tomorrow with more details on the supplemental educational materials.

March 31 update:
To our Newberg and Dundee families,
 
We know you are concerned for your students education in this time of an extended school closure. We are too! We miss doing what we love to do. 
 
Things seem to change every day, and last night the Oregon Department of Education (ODE) made a substantial change to their guidance to us. Staff returned to work yesterday, tackling the project of creating the supplemental educational materials ODE asked us to provide. Now, we are being directed to move to Distance Learning for All and to begin implementation on April 13. 
 
This change was not unanticipated. Last week, our district team began planning for Phase 2 of Remote Learning. Today and tomorrow, well continue the work weve started, creating supplemental educational materials. But know that behind the scenes, weve been working hard over the last two weeks to prepare our systems to deliver remote learning for all our students during an extended closure.

This will be a brand new model that we will create together, and we will prioritize equity in every decision. Its going to be a challenge! But I believe our talented staff will rise to this occasion for our students. We will innovate and build, improving what we do each step of the way. We will partner with families and caregivers to ensure safety and wellness for our students, foster connections and relationships, and center on equity.
 
ODEs guidance is broad at this point; we expect each day to bring new information. Distance Learning for All will include a regular, daily connection with a licensed staff member; a focus on relevant, essential, standards-based learning; teachers, families, and caregivers working as a team to establish learning routines; and teachers reporting on and monitoring each students progress toward learning goals and standards.
We know our high school seniors are particularly impacted by this school closure. Our seniors will have a path to graduation. ODE has not yet outlined pathways to graduation, but we know that the systems we set up will give the competencies and credit opportunities needed when that guidance from ODE is finalized.
We know you have tons of questions we dont have answers to yet. We do too! Well keep in regular contact and get information to you as quickly as we can receive it and process it.
Newberg Public Schools are powered by the best of the best staff: Our teachers have wanted to teach all through this closure. Our classified staff have wanted to love and support our students. Weve been feeding students and checking in. Our students couldnt ask for a better team to work on their behalf.
 
Thank you,
 
Dr. Joe Morelock
Superintendent
Newberg Public Schools


March 27 update:

Hello everyone,

Here is a brief update from Newberg Public Schools today:

I dont have access to a device and/or internet at home, and Ive made a request. When will I receive the device?
Our staff is back on Monday March 30, and will clean and organize all devices. You can expect to hear about how they will be distributed toward the middle or end of the week. If you have a need but havent requested a device, follow this link and fill out the form: https://bit.ly/3bvclVV 

CPRD is opening childcare for essential needs on Monday March 30. Everyone will need to re-enroll for the limited spaces available.
Called Camp Care Essentials, this day care program will run MondayFriday, 7:30 am to 6:00 pm. Pre-K children ages 3-6 will be at Chehalem Community Center; grade school children ages 512 will be at Sander Estate House in Dundee or Chehalem Youth Building in Newberg.
Cost:
$47 per day (registered in advance)
$99 1-week part-time rate (includes up to 19 hours per week of child care)
$125 1-week full-time rate (20 or more hours a week) 
 Registration is open now and closes when the maximum enrollment of ten children per pod/club is met. Registration is online only at the link: https://bit.ly/39jhhvK 
For questions or assistance with online enrollment, contact Chehalem Aquatic and Fitness Center at 503 537-2909 between the hours of 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. Monday through Friday, or email registration@cprdnewberg.org.

March 26 update:
Hello everyone,
 
I hope this message finds you well and safe. I wanted to give you all an update as to the next steps for your students and for our staff. We know you have lots of questions about whats next and what the rest of the year looks like for schools in Oregon. 
 
Four things are being required of us by the governor:
Feed students who are in need;
Provide childcare for emergency workers, medical staff, first responders, and essential staff;
Pay all regular employees;
Provide supplementary educational materials and learning supports.
 
Since the beginning of last week, we have provided meals for students aged 1 to 18 across our district, and this week weve opened additional food service for grab and go lunches at Dundee Elementary. Our foodservice staff have been truly amazing at getting this up and running so quickly, serving upwards of 250 meals a day. We expect this will increase as the closure goes on.

Weve also been preparing for the possibility of providing childcare for our emergency workers, medical staff, first responders, and essential staff. There are still very many details to work out, and we are working with our community and county partners to make this a reality in the coming days. 
 
These are essential priorities for our community and state, and were working hard to serve well. We know your big questions are around education, and what this will look like for our students. At this time, we know we will not reopen our school sites before April 28th, and possibly later should the governor extend the closure. Reopening will depend upon slowing down the spread of the virus in our community and state. 
 
District office staff and administrators have been hard at work setting up the structure to provide supplementary educational materials and learning supports, which parents and guardians can do at home with their children. Beginning Monday, March 30th, our teachers and staff will be meeting (via electronic methods, in compliance with the governors Stay at Home order) to create the materials that will enable a connection with our students. 
 
Will we be moving to full online classes and instruction? 
Not at this time. We continue to work to make sure every student without a device and/or reliable internet has the ability to connect to the communication and resources we are creating. (If you have a need, click here and fill out the form: https://bit.ly/3bvclVV)
 
We continue to work on a system to provide learning supports to accommodate a variety of learners. The Oregon Department of Education (ODE) as of now is giving guidance to work on supplementary educational materials, recognizing the significant challenges in transitioning to direct instruction for every student in an online format. If the closure extends beyond April 28th, we may be directed to move more fully into online instruction. We continue to plan and problem solve for that possibility. For now, the supplementary educational materials are being developed and you will be able to begin accessing them on April 2. These materials will be available on the district website, and we will provide additional communication when they become available.
 
These activities will be developed by teachers and designed to be done at home. Some may be online, others may be paper and pencil, and still others may be more physical in nature. These activities will span the range of the subjects they would normally be taught in school. 
 
How is my senior going to graduate? What about senior projects and essential skills? 
ODE is focusing on seniors as their first priority in this closure. From top state officials to everyone at Newberg High School and Catalyst, we want to get all our seniors across the finish line, even with this unprecedented pandemic. Were waiting to hear the final approval from ODE on the changes they are making to graduation requirements, including the number of earned credits required. Our high school staff will then look at every single senior, evaluate where they are compared to the new requirements, and make an individualized plan for meeting graduation requirements. Each senior will be contacted by school staff to make clear what is ahead. It is likely that some requirements like senior project and essential skills will be waived, but we have not had final word on that yet. Since we do not yet have direction from ODE, it will be several weeks before we are able to communicate with all seniors.
 
What about my freshman/sophomore/junior who may miss out on earning credits this year? This closure could hurt their ability to graduate on time. 
ODE has promised that the next priority after figuring things out for this years seniors is to address the needs of other high school students. We will work with every student for their success in high school as we learn what the guidance is from ODE.
 
What about graduation ceremonies? Will they occur or be rescheduled or canceled?
