DOCS_modelChunk = [{"ty":"is","ibi":86577,"s":"We do not know at this time. It will all depend on the governors orders and whether the spread of this virus can be slowed or contained. We will follow all state guidance.
 
Are students going to have to repeat this years grade level? 
No. We will be adjusting our work at the beginning of next year in all grades to make sure we can provide the supports necessary for your students to receive the grade level content, skills, and standards they need by the end of next year. 
 
What about annual state testing? 
We have been informed Oregon has received a conditional waiver from the Federal government to not administer state testing this year.
 
What about forecasting/scheduling classes for next year? 
We are working on online options for this and will communicate as we have the system and process in place.
 
What about Kindergarten registration scheduled for Tuesday April 7? 
This is canceled due to the school closure. We are working on alternate ways of registering and will communicate as soon as possible.
 
We know the uncertainty is unsettling, for families and for students. We miss the daily chance to do what we love to do, educate our students and prepare them to be contributing citizens to our community. Please know that we are working hard to adapt and serve each of you in these new conditions.
 
Sincerely,
 
Dr. Joe Morelock
Superintendent
Newberg Public Schools

March 23 update:
Today Governor Brown issued a further executive order requiring everyone to stay in their homes except for essential functions. You can review the attached summary, or read the full text of her order here.
 
Through the Oregon Department of Education, we have already received word that the direction previously given to all schools by the governor is to continue under this new order. Therefore, we will continue to provide food at our distribution sites. As we have said, please do not congregate and maintain at least 6 feet of distance between you and anyone else when you pick up your meals. Here are the sites and times for this week:
 
 Edwards Elementary School Cafeteria will serve breakfast from 8-9 am
 Edwards Elementary School Cafeteria will serve lunch from 11 am-12 noon
 CPRD Aquatic Center (1802 Haworth Ave) will serve lunch from 11 am-12 noon 
 Newberg Public Library (503 E. Hancock St.) will serve lunch from 11 am-12 noon
 Deskin Commons will serve lunch from 11:00 am- 11:30 am 
 Dundee Elementary school will serve lunch from 11 am-12 noon (new site starting Monday March 23)
 
In addition, schools may be asked to provide childcare for essential health care workers and first responders. We continue to work on plans for emergency child care, since we know that, too, will continue even with this order by the governor. 
 
Please be safe and also work for the safety of others, including the most vulnerable in our society. This means staying home except for work or other essential needs, and following the governors executive order.
 
Thank you!

March 20 update:
To the students and families of Newberg and Dundee schools,

We miss you, and we miss our normal routines! We hope you are continuing to take the orders from the governor seriously: stay home as much as possible, avoid groups, practice social distancing (at least 6 feet apart as much as possible), and practice good hygiene. This is important even for those who feel well and have no symptoms, in order to slow the spread of the COVID-19 novel coronavirus.

All the staff of our school district wishes you health and as much calm and peace as possible. Schools do more than just schoolwork we care about your mental and emotional health as well. We hope you find ways to check in with people you care about by phone or videochat. These are challenging times, and we shouldnt wait to reach out. There are many options for mental health supports that might be available by phone or online. Remember resources like the Community Wellness Collectives community resource guide available at https://www.communitywellnesscollective.org; the SafeOregon tip line: https://www.safeoregon.com/report-a-tip/; and the Suicide Prevention Hotline: 1-800-273-8255.

We hope information will help lower the stress of these unprecedented times. Heres what we have for you today:

We will continue to provide grab-and-go meals for all children under age 18 through spring break and ongoing throughout the closure. This will be Monday through Friday, and we are adding Dundee Elementary School as a location:
Edwards Elementary School Cafeteria will serve breakfast from 8-9 am
Edwards Elementary School Cafeteria will serve lunch from 11 am-12 noon
CPRD Aquatic Center (1802 Haworth Ave) will serve lunch from 11 am-12 noon 
Newberg Public Library (503 E. Hancock St.) will serve lunch from 11 am-12 noon
Deskin Commons will serve lunch from 11:00 am- 11:30 am
Dundee Elementary school will serve lunch from 11 am-12 noon
Be watching for communication next week, as we have plans to open many more sites on April 1, as well as providing grab-and-go breakfast and lunch meals at one time.

The governor has said schools must be ready to provide childcare for health workers and first responders. CPRD and other partners are working with us as we learn new things each day. We know this is important and will communicate as quickly as possible when options become available. 

We know some students and families do not have access to our communications or other resources because they need a device and/or internet access at their home. If you would like to request to borrow a device and/or need internet access, you can request it with this form. Please assist others who may need this and cant see online communication, offering to fill out the form for them if they dont have a way to do so. We will also be calling students and families after spring break, but wanted to make the form available to those who can access it now: 
English: bit.do/npsdevices 
Espaol: bit.do/npsdispositivos

Principals and the district office have set up a structure for developing supplemental materials as a connection point between teachers and students. These are not designed to replace school. After spring break, teachers will work in teams to develop these materials, and we will share with you how they can be accessed.

This school closure can be especially stressful for high school seniors. The Oregon Department of Education (ODE) is prioritizing how to make a path to get all our seniors across the finish line. They are getting feedback from superintendents across the state on a draft proposal for some ways forward. Our high school administrators are aware of the proposal and will be working over the next two weeks to see where every one of our seniors fits with the new proposal, and then will be contacting each student to develop a plan. Trust that everyone, from state officials to every teacher and educational assistant, is prioritizing how to help our seniors during this closure to make it through to graduation.
We have learned that Advanced Placement (AP) exams will be developed that can be taken online. We dont have specific details yet, but will share that out with AP students when we learn more.

Thanks to all the staff and community who have volunteered to help in many ways! Our community cares. We will keep working to set up structures so that we can help each other most effectively. Stay healthy!

March 17 update:
Hello Newberg and Dundee school families,

This afternoon, Governor Kate Brown announced an extension of the closure of Oregon schools to help slow the spread of COVID-19 (novel coronavirus). Schools will now remain closed until April 28, 2020.

These are trying times, and we are all working together to stay on top of all guidance from the governor and from the Oregon Department of Education (ODE). We are working to get clarification and to understand all that is directed. 

Here is what we know right now:
We will continue to provide grab-and-go meals for all children under 18. Currently, we are trying to get permission to expand our sites, but for now, they remain our summer food distribution sites:
Edwards Elementary School Cafeteria will serve breakfast from 8-9 am

DOCS_modelChunk = [{"ty":"is","ibi":94832,"s":"Edwards Elementary School Cafeteria will serve lunch from 11 am-12 noon
CPRD Aquatic Center (1802 Haworth Ave) will serve lunch from 11 am-12 noon 
Newberg Public Library (503 E. Hancock St.) will serve lunch from 11 am-12 noon
Deskin Commons will serve lunch from 11:00 am- 11:30 am 
We are treating now through March 27 as an extended spring break, and are making plans for supplemental educational materials for students after spring break is over.
Many are asking about switching to online learning. This is a very complex change and we do not anticipate solving all the problems and making that complete switch anytime soon.
We are very mindful of our responsibility to provide an equitable learning experience for every one of our students. Meeting every students needs with specially designed instruction, and ensuring internet access for all students, both present formidable challenges that we are working to overcome. We will continue to follow guidance from the state and work on problem solving.
However, we will work, as the governors order allows, to provide supplementary educational materials for those who are able to access them. Those will not be available until April 1, 2020 at the earliest.

Here are the things we are working on: 

Expanding food distribution to students.
Developing a system of wellness checks for all our students with the longer closure.
Working with CPRD to see if the C.A.R.E. program for childcare can be re-opened.

Here are the things we will not know for some time:
How this closure affects graduation and senior activities.
Whether the school year will be extended with make-up days.
If and when complete online conversion might be possible.

We will continue to be in touch with information as we learn more about this extended closure. In the meantime, please do all you can to prevent the spread of this virus:
Stay home as much as possible
Maintain social distancing (6 feet apart)
Wash hands frequently, cover coughs and sneezes with your arm, avoid touching your face
Gatherings of 10 or more people are discouraged by the U.S. government at this time.

Without a doubt, we need each other at this time. Loss of income and stress and insecurity are real issues on top of the spread of the virus. We will keep working together to support each other!

March 16 update:

Today (March 16) is our first day of what may be a longer than anticipated closure. Gov. Brown this afternoon announced a ban of gatherings of 25 or more people for at least 4 weeks. We anticipate this will extend the school closure, but are waiting on official word.
In the meantime, we encourage everyone to remain home as much as possible, wash hands frequently, avoid touching your face, and maintain 6 feet of distance between other people. We encourage following the governors new guidance, and avoid being around a group of 10 or more people (groups of 25 are banned completely, while we are asked to avoid groups of 10 or more). Weve attached flyers to help think through social distancing: English Espaol
We are hard at work making plans to feed students, brainstorm solutions for extending education in the event of a longer closure, and how to perform wellness checks for all our students over time. Today we handed out more than 40 breakfasts and more than 100 lunches in grab-and-go containers from our multiple sites.
We will continue to update regularly as we learn information from the state. Until then, our wish is for as much peace and health as you can find. Check in on vulnerable people in your friendship circles. Find ways to connect over the phone or video chat. Connection is important for our mental
